@database "Multiple Paste Guide"
@author "Heiko Schr—der"
@$VER: 3.1 (Release 3)
@wordwrap

@node Main "Multiple Paste V3.1"
                               @{" < Table of Contents" link "Macro-Package.guide/Main"}

@{fg shine}Benifits:@{fg text}
   With this macro you can copy objects accuratly.
   However many objects, whatever types of objects and/or however many copies
   you require. It is all now a question of the knowing what you want.

@{fg shine}Requirements:@{fg text}
   None.

@{fg shine}Using the @{"macro" system "Sys:Utilities/Multiview MPaste.iff"}:@{fg text}

   First you choose 1 or more graphic object(s).

   @{fg fill}M@{fg text}ode
      You have a choice of how you copy the files.

      Normal  - Your current FinalWriter window size will be used. This can
                slow down the copying.
      Fast    - The Document zoom will to the largest possible percentage.
                This results in a great speed increase.

   @{fg shine}Hint:@{fg text}
      With EPS-Graphics, £Fast¨ takes a longer time to work.
      So for EPS-Graphics, use £Normal¨

   @{fg fill}C@{fg text}opies
      Here you state how many copies you want.

   @{fg fill}P@{fg text}age
      This is where you can chose which page the copies should go on,
      (also of still not previous page).

   Move
      Here you give a distance which will be how far the objects will be moved
      from the previous object, you can choose
         - @{fg fill}h@{fg text}orizontal
      or
         - @{fg fill}v@{fg text}ertical
      movement.

   @{fg fill}R@{fg text}otation
      Here you can select any amount of rotation you want.

                     - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - 

   @{fg fill}A@{fg text}pply
      Starts the macro copying.
      A bar will apear at the bottom of the page showing aproximatly how far
      through the procedure the macro is.

   @{fg fill}U@{fg text}ndo
      Deletes all of the objects that the macro has just created.

   @{fg fill}C@{fg text}ancel
   @{fg fill}ESC@{fg text} or closing the window
      Terminates the Macro.

@endnode
